readingPassages.push(
{
    title:'6. Artificial Intelligence',
    text:`<h3>Artificial Intelligence: Promise and Peril</h3><p>Artificial intelligence (AI) has emerged as one of the most transformative technologies of the 21st century. From virtual assistants to systems that diagnose diseases and drive cars, AI is reshaping nearly every industry. The global AI market is projected to reach over $500 billion by 2030.</p><p>The benefits of AI are substantial. In healthcare, AI algorithms can analyze medical images with accuracy rivaling experienced doctors, enabling earlier cancer detection. In education, AI-powered tutoring systems adapt to individual learning styles, providing personalized instruction impossible in traditional classrooms. In transportation, self-driving vehicles promise to reduce accidents—over 90% of which are caused by human error.</p><p>However, rapid AI advancement raises significant concerns. Economists predict up to 30% of current jobs could be automated within two decades. There are also ethical concerns about privacy, as AI systems require vast amounts of personal data. Additionally, the potential misuse of AI for surveillance and social control has alarmed civil liberties organizations worldwide.</p><p>Governments are now grappling with how to regulate AI. The European Union has proposed comprehensive AI legislation, while other countries take a more cautious approach. Experts emphasize developing AI responsibly, ensuring benefits are shared while minimizing potential harms. The key question is whether regulation can keep pace with technological change.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What is the projected AI market value by 2030?',opts:['$100 billion','$500 billion','$1 trillion','$50 billion'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "projected to reach over $500 billion by 2030."'},{type:'tf',q:'AI can help detect cancer earlier in some cases.',ans:'true',exp:'第二段提到AI enables earlier cancer detection。'},{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of jobs could be automated within two decades?',opts:['Up to 10%','Up to 30%','Up to 50%','Up to 70%'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "up to 30% of current jobs could be automated."'},{type:'tf',q:'All countries have agreed on a unified approach to AI regulation.',ans:'false',exp:'第四段提到EU和other countries有不同approach。'}]
},
{
    title:'7. Climate Change and Food',
    text:`<h3>Climate Change and Global Food Security</h3><p>Climate change poses one of the greatest threats to global food security. Rising temperatures, changing rainfall patterns, and increasingly frequent extreme weather events are affecting crop yields worldwide. According to the United Nations, global food production could decline by up to 30% by 2050 if current trends continue.</p><p>The impact varies by region. In tropical areas, even small temperature increases significantly reduce yields of staple crops such as wheat, rice, and maize. Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia are particularly vulnerable, as these regions already face food insecurity with limited adaptation resources. In contrast, some temperate regions may initially benefit from longer growing seasons, though these advantages are likely offset by increased pest pressure and water scarcity.</p><p>Scientists and farmers are developing adaptation strategies, including drought-resistant crop varieties, improved irrigation efficiency, and diversified farming systems. Agroforestry—integrating trees with crops and livestock—shows promise in making farms more resilient to climate variability while sequestering carbon.</p><p>However, adaptation alone is insufficient. Reducing greenhouse gas emissions remains essential. Agriculture itself accounts for about 25% of global emissions, meaning changes in farming practices—reducing fertilizer use, adopting plant-based diets—can contribute significantly to the solution.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'By how much could food production decline by 2050?',opts:['Up to 10%','Up to 30%','Up to 50%','Up to 70%'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "global food production could decline by up to 30% by 2050."'},{type:'tf',q:'Temperate regions will definitely benefit from climate change.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段说advantages likely offset by pest pressure and water scarcity。'},{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of global emissions comes from agriculture?',opts:['About 10%','About 25%','About 50%','About 75%'],ans:'1',exp:'第四段: "accounts for about 25% of global emissions."'}]
},
{
    title:'8. The Sharing Economy',
    text:`<h3>The Sharing Economy: Redefining Ownership</h3><p>The sharing economy—also known as the gig economy—has fundamentally changed how people access goods and services. Companies like Uber, Airbnb, and Didi have disrupted traditional industries by allowing individuals to share cars, homes, and assets through digital platforms. The sector has grown exponentially, valued at over $335 billion by 2025.</p><p>Proponents highlight several advantages. For consumers, sharing platforms provide cheaper, more convenient alternatives to traditional services. For asset owners, they create new income streams—an Airbnb host earns from a spare room, while an Uber driver uses their car to generate income during free time. From an environmental perspective, sharing underutilized assets can reduce waste by maximizing use of existing goods rather than manufacturing new ones.</p><p>However, the sharing economy has attracted criticism. One major concern is worker protections—gig workers are typically classified as independent contractors, lacking benefits such as health insurance, paid leave, and pensions. There are also safety and regulatory concerns, as many platforms have operated in legal grey areas, bypassing regulations for traditional industries.</p><p>Governments worldwide are updating regulatory frameworks. Some cities have imposed limits on short-term rentals in response to housing affordability concerns. Others have introduced legislation to improve gig worker conditions. The challenge is balancing innovation and flexibility with adequate consumer and worker protections.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'The sharing economy has grown slowly in recent years.',ans:'false',exp:'第一段说grown exponentially。'},{type:'mc',q:'What environmental benefit does the sharing economy offer?',opts:['Creating more manufacturing jobs','Reducing waste by maximizing use of existing goods','Increasing fuel consumption','Building more factories'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "reduce waste by maximizing use of existing goods."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is a major criticism of the sharing economy?',opts:['It is too expensive','Gig workers lack employee benefits','It creates too many permanent jobs','It has no digital platforms'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "gig workers... lack access to benefits such as health insurance."'}]
},
{
    title:'9. Language Extinction',
    text:`<h3>The Disappearing Languages of the World</h3><p>Of approximately 7,000 languages spoken today, linguists estimate 50-90% will become extinct by the end of this century. On average, one language dies every two weeks. This represents not just the loss of communication systems, but the disappearance of unique cultural worldviews, traditional knowledge, and historical records.</p><p>The primary driver is globalization. As communities connect to the global economy, speakers of minority languages shift to dominant languages such as English, Mandarin, or Spanish to access better opportunities. Parents may choose not to teach their native language to children, believing fluency in a dominant language gives competitive advantage.</p><p>The consequences extend beyond communication. Languages encode unique knowledge about local ecosystems, medicinal plants, and sustainable living accumulated over thousands of years. When a language dies, this knowledge often dies with it. Furthermore, language is tied to identity—loss of ancestral language contributes to cultural disconnection and decreased self-esteem among indigenous communities.</p><p>Preservation efforts have increased. UNESCO maintains an atlas of endangered languages, and organizations document languages through recordings and written materials. Digital technology creates new opportunities—mobile apps, online dictionaries, and social media engage younger generations with their heritage languages.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'Linguists estimate 50-90% of languages will disappear by 2100.',ans:'true',exp:'第一段明确提到。'},{type:'mc',q:'What is the main reason for language extinction?',opts:['Climate change','Globalization','Lack of writing systems','Government bans'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "The primary driver... is globalization."'},{type:'tf',q:'Languages only contain communication systems with no other value.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段说Languages encode unique knowledge about ecosystems等。'},{type:'mc',q:'How often does a language die?',opts:['Every day','Every week','Every two weeks','Every month'],ans:'2',exp:'第一段: "one language dies every two weeks."'}]
},
{
    title:'10. Renewable Energy',
    text:`<h3>The Transition to Renewable Energy</h3><p>The global transition from fossil fuels to renewables is a defining challenge of our time. Solar, wind, hydroelectric, and geothermal power offer clean, sustainable energy without the carbon emissions driving climate change. Over the past decade, solar panel costs have fallen over 80%, making renewables increasingly competitive with fossil fuels.</p><p>Several countries have made remarkable progress. Costa Rica generated over 98% of its electricity from renewable sources in 2020, primarily hydropower. Denmark regularly produces over 40% of electricity from wind power. China, the world's largest carbon emitter, has also become the largest renewable energy investor, accounting for nearly half of global investment.</p><p>However, significant obstacles remain. The intermittent nature of solar and wind power—the sun doesn't always shine and wind doesn't always blow—poses challenges for grid stability. Energy storage technologies are improving but remain expensive at scale. There are also political barriers, including opposition from fossil fuel industries and high upfront infrastructure costs.</p><p>Most experts agree the transition to low-carbon energy is not only possible but inevitable. The key question is not whether but how quickly. Accelerating this transition requires sustained government investment, technological innovation, and international cooperation on an unprecedented scale.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'By how much have solar panel costs fallen in the past decade?',opts:['Over 20%','Over 50%','Over 80%','Over 95%'],ans:'2',exp:'第一段: "solar panel costs have fallen over 80%."'},{type:'tf',q:'Costa Rica generates most of its electricity from renewables.',ans:'true',exp:'第二段: "over 98% of its electricity from renewable sources."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is a major challenge for solar and wind power?',opts:['Too much energy production','Intermittent nature','Too quiet','Excessive water use'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "The intermittent nature of solar and wind power."'}]
},
{
    title:'11. Social Media and Mental Health',
    text:`<h3>Social Media and Adolescent Mental Health</h3><p>The relationship between social media use and mental health, particularly among adolescents, has become a topic of intense public concern. With teenagers spending 3-5 hours daily on social media, researchers investigate whether this unprecedented digital engagement contributes to rising rates of anxiety, depression, and other mental health issues.</p><p>Several studies find correlations between heavy social media use and poor mental health. A 2019 JAMA study found adolescents spending over three hours daily on social media were at significantly higher risk for mental health problems. Researchers suggest several mechanisms: social comparison—seeing curated highlights of others' lives—can lead to inadequacy; cyberbullying causes psychological distress; and platform addictiveness disrupts sleep patterns.</p><p>However, the picture is nuanced. Some research suggests moderate use has positive effects: providing social support, facilitating self-expression, and helping young people maintain friendships. The quality of online interactions appears to matter more than quantity of screen time.</p><p>In response, several countries have proposed legislation to better protect young users. The UK's Age Appropriate Design Code requires platforms to prioritize children's privacy. Some schools have implemented phone-free policies. Mental health organizations recommend parents establish clear screen time boundaries and encourage face-to-face activities.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'Teenagers spend 3-5 hours daily on social media.',ans:'true',exp:'第一段明确提到。'},{type:'mc',q:'What does social comparison on social media lead to?',opts:['Increased confidence','Feelings of inadequacy','Better grades','Improved health'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "can lead to feelings of inadequacy."'},{type:'mc',q:'What matters more than screen time according to research?',opts:['Phone brand','Quality of online interactions','Number of followers','App design'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "quality of online interactions appears to matter more."'}]
},
{
    title:'12. Space Exploration',
    text:`<h3>The New Space Race</h3><p>After decades of government-dominated space exploration, a new era has begun—driven increasingly by private companies. SpaceX, Blue Origin, and Virgin Galactic have dramatically reduced launch costs, opening possibilities once confined to science fiction. The cost of sending a kilogram into space has fallen from about $18,500 during the Shuttle era to roughly $2,700 today.</p><p>This new space race has several key objectives: establishing permanent human settlements beyond Earth, space tourism—with companies offering suborbital flights to wealthy customers, and deploying mega-constellations of satellites like Starlink to provide global broadband internet.</p><p>However, rapid expansion has created new problems. Space debris—defunct satellites, spent rocket stages, and collision fragments—poses serious threats. Over 30,000 tracked pieces of orbital debris larger than 10 centimeters exist, plus millions of smaller fragments. A single collision could trigger the Kessler Syndrome, making certain orbits unusable for generations.</p><p>The legal framework for space activities remains underdeveloped. The 1967 Outer Space Treaty established basic principles—prohibiting weapons of mass destruction in space and stating space should benefit all humanity. However, the treaty says little about private commercial activities, resource extraction from celestial bodies, or environmental protection of space.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What was the cost per kg to space during the Shuttle era?',opts:['$2,700','$18,500','$50,000','$100,000'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "from about $18,500 during the Space Shuttle era."'},{type:'tf',q:'Space debris has become a serious threat to spacecraft.',ans:'true',exp:'第三段: "Space debris... poses serious threats."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is the Kessler Syndrome?',opts:['A medical condition','A cascade effect of space collisions','A rocket technology','A satellite type'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "a cascade effect known as the Kessler Syndrome."'}]
},
{
    title:'13. The Aging Population',
    text:`<h3>The Global Challenge of Aging Populations</h3><p>The world's population is aging at an unprecedented rate. According to WHO, people aged 60+ will double from 1 billion in 2020 to 2.1 billion by 2050. This demographic shift, driven by declining birth rates and increasing life expectancy, creates profound social, economic, and healthcare challenges worldwide.</p><p>The economic implications are significant. As the working-age proportion declines relative to retirees, pension systems face increasing strain. In Japan, with the world's oldest population—nearly 30% over 65—there are fewer than two working-age people per retiree. This has forced the government to raise retirement age and encourage older workers to remain in the workforce.</p><p>Healthcare systems are under pressure. Older populations require more medical care, particularly for chronic conditions like heart disease, diabetes, and dementia. Dementia care costs alone are projected to reach $2 trillion globally by 2030. Many countries struggle to train enough healthcare workers for growing geriatric care demand.</p><p>However, aging populations are not solely a burden. Older people contribute significantly through volunteer work, childcare for grandchildren, and knowledge transfer to younger generations. The concept of "active aging"—promoting health, participation, and security—has gained traction. Policies supporting lifelong learning, flexible retirement, and age-friendly environments can help societies benefit from the longevity revolution.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'People over 60 will double by 2050.',ans:'true',exp:'第一段明确提到。'},{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of Japan\'s population is over 65?',opts:['About 10%','About 20%','Nearly 30%','Over 50%'],ans:'2',exp:'第二段: "nearly 30% of its people over 65."'},{type:'tf',q:'An aging population has only negative effects.',ans:'false',exp:'第四段说Older people contribute significantly through volunteer work等。'}]
},
{
    title:'14. Fast Fashion',
    text:`<h3>The Environmental Cost of Fast Fashion</h3><p>The fashion industry is among the world's largest polluters, responsible for approximately 10% of global carbon emissions and nearly 20% of global wastewater. The rise of "fast fashion"—cheap, trendy clothing produced rapidly in response to latest styles—has dramatically accelerated environmental impact over two decades.</p><p>Environmental damage begins at production. Cotton farming uses vast water and pesticides—a single cotton t-shirt requires about 2,700 liters of water, equivalent to one person's drinking water for 2.5 years. Synthetic fabrics like polyester shed microplastics into waterways with every wash. Textile dyeing involves thousands of chemicals, many toxic, polluting rivers in manufacturing countries.</p><p>The problem continues after purchase. Consumers now buy 60% more clothing than 15 years ago but keep items half as long. An estimated 85% of textiles end up in landfills or incinerators annually—equivalent to one garbage truck of clothing dumped every second. Donated clothes that cannot be sold locally are shipped to developing nations, often undermining local textile industries.</p><p>Interest in sustainable alternatives is growing: buying second-hand, supporting brands using recycled materials, embracing "slow fashion." Some governments have acted—France banned destruction of unsold clothing, requiring donation or recycling. However, experts argue systemic change in production models is ultimately necessary.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of global carbon emissions comes from fashion?',opts:['About 5%','About 10%','About 20%','About 30%'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "approximately 10% of global carbon emissions."'},{type:'tf',q:'Cotton production uses very little water.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: "a single cotton t-shirt requires about 2,700 liters of water."'},{type:'mc',q:'How much more clothing do consumers buy compared to 15 years ago?',opts:['20% more','40% more','60% more','100% more'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段: "60% more clothing than they did 15 years ago."'}]
},
{
    title:'15. Gene Editing Ethics',
    text:`<h3>CRISPR and the Ethics of Gene Editing</h3><p>CRISPR-Cas9, a revolutionary gene-editing technology, gives scientists unprecedented ability to modify DNA with precision. Since its 2012 discovery, CRISPR has been used in research from disease-resistant crops to potential cures for genetic disorders like sickle cell disease and certain blindness forms.</p><p>The medical potential is extraordinary. In 2023, the UK became the first country to approve CRISPR-based therapy for sickle cell disease. Researchers explore using gene editing to make cells resistant to HIV, engineer immune cells fighting cancer, and address hundreds of single-gene mutation diseases.</p><p>However, gene editing raises profound ethical questions. The most controversial application is germline editing—modifying human embryos with changes passed to future generations. In 2018, a Chinese scientist announced creating the world's first gene-edited babies, leading to widespread condemnation. Critics worry germline editing could lead to "designer babies," exacerbating inequality and introducing unforeseen health consequences.</p><p>The international community grapples with regulation. Many countries prohibit germline editing, but rules vary widely. Some fear a regulatory "race to the bottom" with scientists seeking jurisdictions with minimal oversight. WHO has established a global registry for human genome editing research and called for a moratorium on clinical applications altering the human germline until implications are better understood.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'When was CRISPR-Cas9 discovered?',opts:['2008','2012','2016','2020'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "Since its 2012 discovery."'},{type:'tf',q:'The UK was the first country to approve CRISPR therapy.',ans:'true',exp:'第二段: "UK became the first country to approve a CRISPR-based therapy."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is germline editing?',opts:['Editing plant genes only','Editing embryos with changes passed to future generations','Editing adult genes only','Editing bacterial genes'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "editing of human embryos... changes that can be passed down to future generations."'}]
},
{
    title:'16. The Gender Pay Gap',
    text:`<h3>Understanding the Gender Pay Gap</h3><p>The gender pay gap remains a persistent feature of labor markets worldwide. According to the ILO, women globally earn approximately 20% less than men on average. While the gap has narrowed in many countries, progress is slow—at current rates, it would take over 250 years to close completely.</p><p>The causes are complex. One factor is occupational segregation—women are overrepresented in lower-paying sectors like care work, education, and retail, while men dominate higher-paying fields like engineering, finance, and technology. Even within the same occupation, women often earn less, partly because they are less likely to negotiate starting salaries and more likely to take career breaks for child-rearing.</p><p>The "motherhood penalty" is well-documented. Having children negatively affects women's earnings and career progression, while fathers experience a "fatherhood bonus"—higher earnings after having children. This disparity links to traditional gender norms placing primary childcare responsibility on women.</p><p>Governments have introduced legislation addressing the pay gap. Iceland, often ranked most gender-equal, requires companies with 25+ employees to obtain equal pay certification. Several countries mandate gender pay gap reporting by large employers. While these measures increase transparency, closing the gap requires addressing deeper cultural and structural barriers.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'The global gender pay gap is about 20%.',ans:'true',exp:'第一段: "women globally earn approximately 20% less than men."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is the "motherhood penalty"?',opts:['A government tax','Negative impact of children on women\'s earnings','A fine for working mothers','Healthcare costs'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "Having children negatively affects women\'s earnings."'},{type:'mc',q:'Which country requires equal pay certification?',opts:['USA','China','Iceland','Brazil'],ans:'2',exp:'第四段: "Iceland... requires companies... to obtain equal pay certification."'}]
},
{
    title:'17. Antibiotic Resistance',
    text:`<h3>The Looming Crisis of Antibiotic Resistance</h3><p>Antibiotics are among medicine's most important discoveries, saving millions from once-fatal infections. However, overuse and misuse have led to antibiotic-resistant "superbugs." WHO has declared antimicrobial resistance a top ten global public health threat.</p><p>The scale is alarming. An estimated 1.27 million deaths were directly attributable to antibiotic-resistant infections in 2019, projected to rise to 10 million annually by 2050—potentially surpassing cancer as a leading cause of death. Common procedures like cesarean sections, hip replacements, and chemotherapy—which rely on antibiotics to prevent infections—could become too risky to perform routinely.</p><p>The causes are well understood. Doctor overprescription—often for viral infections where antibiotics are useless—is a major factor. In agriculture, antibiotics are routinely given to healthy livestock to promote growth and prevent disease, accounting for roughly 70% of global antibiotic use. Poor sanitation and inadequate infection control in healthcare also contribute.</p><p>Addressing this requires coordinated global response: developing new antibiotics (though pharmaceutical companies have little incentive to invest in sparingly-used drugs), reducing unnecessary antibiotic use in medicine and agriculture, improving diagnostic tools, and strengthening hospital infection prevention. Public education is also crucial—many people still demand antibiotics for conditions like the common cold that don't require them.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'How many deaths were caused by antibiotic resistance in 2019?',opts:['500,000','1.27 million','5 million','10 million'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "1.27 million deaths... in 2019."'},{type:'tf',q:'Antibiotics are effective against viral infections.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段: "often for viral infections against which antibiotics are useless."'},{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of global antibiotics is used in agriculture?',opts:['About 30%','About 50%','Roughly 70%','About 90%'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段: "roughly 70% of global antibiotic use."'}]
},
{
    title:'18. Psychology of Happiness',
    text:`<h3>What Science Tells Us About Happiness</h3><p>For centuries, philosophers pondered happiness. In recent decades, psychologists and neuroscientists have used empirical methods to understand what actually makes people happy. The emerging field of positive psychology has challenged many common assumptions about human well-being.</p><p>One robust finding: beyond a certain threshold—around $75,000 annually in the US—additional income has little impact on day-to-day happiness. While money reduces poverty-related stress, once basic needs are met, other factors become far more important: quality of close relationships, a sense of purpose, regular physical activity, and practicing gratitude.</p><p>Relationships emerge as perhaps the most important factor. The Harvard Study of Adult Development, tracking 700+ men for over 80 years, found close relationship quality was the strongest predictor of both happiness and physical health in old age—more important than cholesterol, wealth, or social class. People satisfied with relationships at 50 were the healthiest at 80.</p><p>Good news from research: a significant portion of happiness is within our control. Genetics accounts for roughly 50% of happiness variation, life circumstances about 10%, leaving 40% determined by intentional activities—what people choose to do and think. Practices like expressing gratitude, savoring positive experiences, performing kindness, and investing in relationships can measurably increase well-being.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'Beyond what income does money have little impact on happiness?',opts:['$30,000','$50,000','$75,000','$100,000'],ans:'2',exp:'第二段: "around $75,000 annually in the US."'},{type:'tf',q:'Relationships are the strongest predictor of happiness in old age.',ans:'true',exp:'第三段: "the strongest predictor of both happiness and physical health."'},{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of happiness is determined by intentional activities?',opts:['10%','25%','40%','50%'],ans:'2',exp:'第四段: "the remaining 40% is determined by intentional activities."'}]
},
{
    title:'19. Ocean Acidification',
    text:`<h3>The Silent Crisis: Ocean Acidification</h3><p>While climate change dominates environmental discussions, a related phenomenon—ocean acidification—is called global warming's "evil twin." As oceans absorb about 30% of atmospheric CO2, seawater chemistry changes in ways threatening marine ecosystems worldwide.</p><p>The chemistry is straightforward: CO2 dissolving in seawater forms carbonic acid, lowering pH. Since the Industrial Revolution, average ocean surface pH has fallen from 8.2 to 8.1—a 30% acidity increase. If trends continue, acidity could increase 150% by century's end—a rate unprecedented in 300 million years.</p><p>Impacts on marine life are already observed. Organisms building shells from calcium carbonate—oysters, clams, corals, plankton—struggle in more acidic waters. Coral reefs, the rainforests of the sea, are particularly vulnerable: warming plus acidification causes widespread bleaching. The Great Barrier Reef has lost over half its coral cover since 1985.</p><p>Socioeconomic consequences are equally concerning. About 3 billion people depend on marine biodiversity for livelihoods. The global economic value of marine ecosystem services is estimated at $3-6 trillion annually. Shellfish industries in the US Pacific Northwest have already experienced significant acidification losses—a preview for other coastal communities. Addressing ocean acidification requires the same solution as climate change: rapid, substantial CO2 emission reductions.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'Oceans absorb about 30% of atmospheric CO2.',ans:'true',exp:'第一段: "the oceans absorb about 30% of the carbon dioxide."'},{type:'mc',q:'How much has ocean acidity increased since the Industrial Revolution?',opts:['10%','30%','50%','100%'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "a 30% increase in acidity."'},{type:'mc',q:'How many people depend on marine biodiversity?',opts:['1 billion','3 billion','5 billion','7 billion'],ans:'1',exp:'第四段: "About 3 billion people depend on marine biodiversity."'}]
},
{
    title:'20. The Future of Work',
    text:`<h3>Automation, AI, and the Future of Employment</h3><p>The nature of work undergoes fundamental transformation. Automation, AI, and technological advances reshape industries and redefine required skills. While previous technological change primarily affected routine manual labor, the current revolution increasingly impacts cognitive tasks once thought to require human intelligence.</p><p>Job loss predictions vary widely. A frequently cited 2013 Oxford study estimated 47% of US jobs were at high automation risk within two decades. More recent OECD analyses suggest a lower but still substantial 14% of jobs being highly automatable, with another 32% experiencing significant changes. Few occupations will remain entirely untouched.</p><p>However, history shows technology creates jobs as well as destroys them. Many common jobs today—social media manager, app developer, data scientist—didn't exist 20 years ago. The challenge is ensuring workers have skills and support to transition into new roles. This requires significant investment in lifelong learning, with education available throughout careers, not confined to early decades.</p><p>The policy implications are profound. Some advocate universal basic income in response to technological unemployment. Others emphasize portable benefits following workers regardless of employment status—particularly benefiting gig economy workers. Nearly all experts agree resisting technological change is neither feasible nor desirable; the task is managing transition to share benefits widely while protecting vulnerable workers.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What did the Oxford study estimate about job automation?',opts:['14% at risk','32% at risk','47% at risk','80% at risk'],ans:'2',exp:'第二段: "47% of US jobs were at high risk."'},{type:'tf',q:'Technology only destroys jobs, never creates new ones.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段: "technology creates jobs as well as destroys them."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is proposed as a response to technological unemployment?',opts:['More factory jobs','Universal basic income','Shorter work weeks','Less technology'],ans:'1',exp:'第四段: "universal basic income as a response to technological unemployment."'}]
},
{
    title:'21. The History of the Internet',
    text:`<h3>The History of the Internet: From Military Project to Global Network</h3><p>The internet, now an indispensable part of daily life for billions, began as a modest military research project. In 1969, the US Department of Defense's Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA) created ARPANET, connecting four university computers. The initial goal was to build a decentralized communication network that could survive a nuclear attack. No one at the time could have predicted that this experiment would evolve into the global communication system we know today.</p><p>The 1970s and 1980s saw crucial technical developments. In 1974, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn published the TCP/IP protocol, which remains the foundation of internet communication. The term "Internet" was first used in 1974 to describe a network of networks. In 1989, Tim Berners-Lee, a British computer scientist working at CERN, proposed the World Wide Web—a system of interlinked hypertext documents accessible via the internet. This invention transformed the internet from a tool used mainly by academics and military personnel into a platform anyone could navigate.</p><p>The 1990s witnessed explosive growth. The first graphical web browser, Mosaic, was released in 1993, making the web visually accessible. Companies like Netscape, Yahoo, and Amazon were founded shortly after. By the year 2000, over 360 million people were online—a dramatic increase from just 2.6 million in 1990. The dot-com bubble of the late 1990s saw enormous investment in internet companies. While many failed, survivors like Amazon and Google went on to become some of the world's most valuable corporations.</p><p>Today, over 5 billion people use the internet, and its influence extends to every aspect of modern life—commerce, education, healthcare, entertainment, and politics. However, challenges have emerged: concerns about privacy, the spread of misinformation, cybersecurity threats, and the digital divide between those with and without reliable internet access. As we look to the future, technologies like satellite internet and 5G promise to connect the remaining unconnected populations, while debates about regulation and digital rights continue to shape the internet's evolution.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'ARPANET was initially created for military purposes.',ans:'true',exp:'第一段明确提到ARPA是国防部下属机构，最初目标是建立能承受核攻击的通信网络。'},{type:'mc',q:'Who proposed the World Wide Web in 1989?',opts:['Vint Cerf','Bob Kahn','Tim Berners-Lee','Bill Gates'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段: "Tim Berners-Lee proposed the World Wide Web."'},{type:'mc',q:'How many people were online by the year 2000?',opts:['2.6 million','Over 360 million','1 billion','5 billion'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "By the year 2000, over 360 million people were online."'},{type:'tf',q:'The digital divide refers to the difference in internet speeds between countries.',ans:'false',exp:'第四段提到digital divide指有网络接入与无网络接入人群之间的差距，而非速度差异。'}]
},
{
    title:'22. Coral Reef Destruction',
    text:`<h3>The Crisis Facing Coral Reef Ecosystems</h3><p>Coral reefs are among Earth's most biodiverse ecosystems, often called "the rainforests of the sea." Though covering less than 1% of the ocean floor, they support approximately 25% of all marine life. An estimated 500 million people depend on reefs for food, coastal protection, and livelihoods from fishing and tourism. The global economic value of coral reefs is estimated at $375 billion annually.</p><p>However, reefs face an unprecedented crisis. Since the 1950s, the world has lost approximately half of its coral cover. The primary driver is rising ocean temperatures, which cause coral bleaching—when stressed corals expel the symbiotic algae that provide them with food and color. Without these algae, corals turn white and typically die within weeks if temperatures do not return to normal. The Great Barrier Reef has experienced six major bleaching events since 1998, with the most severe in 2016 and 2017 affecting over two-thirds of the reef.</p><p>Additional threats compound the crisis. Ocean acidification, caused by absorption of excess atmospheric CO2, reduces the ability of corals to build their calcium carbonate skeletons. Overfishing disrupts the ecological balance by removing herbivorous fish that keep algae in check. Agricultural runoff introduces nutrients that fuel algal blooms, smothering corals. Coastal development and destructive fishing practices like blast fishing cause direct physical damage. Scientists estimate that if current trends continue, over 90% of coral reefs could be threatened by 2030.</p><p>Conservation efforts are underway globally. Approaches include establishing marine protected areas, restoring damaged reefs by transplanting coral fragments, and breeding heat-resistant "super corals" that can withstand warmer waters. However, scientists emphasize that local conservation efforts alone cannot save reefs. Addressing the root cause—climate change—through rapid reduction of greenhouse gas emissions remains essential for the long-term survival of these irreplaceable ecosystems.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of marine life do coral reefs support?',opts:['10%','25%','50%','75%'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "approximately 25% of all marine life."'},{type:'tf',q:'Coral bleaching occurs when water becomes too cold.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段指出bleaching由rising ocean temperatures引起，不是寒冷。'},{type:'mc',q:'How many major bleaching events has the Great Barrier Reef experienced since 1998?',opts:['Three','Four','Five','Six'],ans:'3',exp:'第二段: "six major bleaching events since 1998."'}]
},
{
    title:'23. The Psychology of Advertising',
    text:`<h3>How Advertising Influences Consumer Behavior</h3><p>Advertising is one of the most pervasive forces in modern life. The average person is exposed to between 4,000 and 10,000 advertisements daily through television, social media, billboards, and other channels. The global advertising industry was valued at over $700 billion in 2023, reflecting its central role in the consumer economy. But how exactly does advertising shape our decisions?</p><p>Psychologists have identified several mechanisms through which advertising works. One is the "mere exposure effect"—the finding that people tend to develop a preference for things merely because they are familiar with them. Repeated exposure to a brand logo or jingle creates a sense of trust and liking, even if consumers cannot recall consciously seeing the advertisement. Another mechanism is emotional conditioning: advertisements pair products with positive emotions—happiness, success, attractiveness, social acceptance—creating unconscious associations. Neuromarketing research using brain imaging has shown that these emotional responses often override rational decision-making processes.</p><p>Advertising also exploits cognitive biases. The "bandwagon effect" is leveraged through messages like "America's best-selling brand" or "Join millions who have switched." Social proof—the tendency to copy others' behavior—makes testimonials and influencer endorsements effective. Scarcity tactics ("limited time offer," "only 3 left") create urgency by triggering loss aversion. Research suggests these techniques are so effective that simply being aware of them does not eliminate their influence.</p><p>In response to concerns about manipulative advertising, regulations have been strengthened in many countries. The UK banned junk food advertising before 9pm on television in 2022 to address childhood obesity. The European Union's GDPR gives consumers more control over targeted advertising. However, the line between persuasion and manipulation remains hotly debated. As artificial intelligence enables increasingly personalized advertising, the ethical questions surrounding advertising's influence on human behavior will only grow more urgent.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'How many advertisements is the average person exposed to daily?',opts:['1,000–2,000','4,000–10,000','15,000–20,000','50,000+'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "between 4,000 and 10,000 advertisements."'},{type:'tf',q:'Being aware of advertising techniques eliminates their influence.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段最后: "simply being aware of them does not eliminate their influence."'},{type:'mc',q:'What did the UK ban in 2022 related to advertising?',opts:['All TV advertising','Junk food advertising before 9pm','Social media advertising','Alcohol advertising'],ans:'1',exp:'第四段: "banned junk food advertising before 9pm on television."'}]
},
{
    title:'24. Animal Intelligence',
    text:`<h3>Rethinking Animal Intelligence</h3><p>For centuries, humans have viewed intelligence as a uniquely human trait, drawing a sharp line between our cognitive abilities and those of other animals. However, decades of research in comparative psychology and ethology have fundamentally challenged this assumption, revealing remarkable cognitive abilities across a wide range of species.</p><p>Tool use, once considered a defining human characteristic, has been documented in numerous species. Chimpanzees fashion sticks to extract termites from mounds, while New Caledonian crows bend wires into hooks to retrieve food from containers. Even more impressive is the capacity for social learning and cultural transmission. Dolphin pods in Shark Bay, Australia, have been observed using marine sponges as tools to protect their snouts while foraging—a behavior passed from mother to calf, constituting a form of animal "culture." Octopuses have demonstrated problem-solving abilities that rival those of primates, including opening jars, navigating mazes, and even recognizing individual humans.</p><p>Perhaps most striking is evidence of metacognition—awareness of one's own knowledge—in species including dolphins, rats, and some birds. In experiments, these animals can assess whether they know the answer to a problem and will seek more information when uncertain. Elephants have passed the mirror self-recognition test, suggesting self-awareness comparable to that of great apes and human toddlers. The discovery of spindle neurons—specialized brain cells associated with social emotions—in whale and elephant brains has blurred another line once thought to separate humans from other animals.</p><p>These findings have ethical implications. If animals possess complex cognitive abilities and emotional lives, arguments for their protection and welfare become stronger. Several countries have recognized dolphins and great apes as "non-human persons" with legal rights. While debates continue about defining and measuring intelligence across species, the evidence increasingly suggests that human cognitive uniqueness has been overstated, and that intelligence exists on a spectrum across the animal kingdom.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'Tool use is unique to humans.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段说明黑猩猩、乌鸦等多种动物都使用工具。'},{type:'mc',q:'What do dolphins in Shark Bay use as tools?',opts:['Sticks','Rocks','Marine sponges','Shells'],ans:'2',exp:'第二段: "using marine sponges as tools to protect their snouts."'},{type:'mc',q:'What does metacognition refer to?',opts:['Using tools','Awareness of one\'s own knowledge','Social learning','Mirror recognition'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "awareness of one\'s own knowledge."'}]
},
{
    title:'25. The Industrial Revolution',
    text:`<h3>The Industrial Revolution and Its Lasting Impact</h3><p>The Industrial Revolution, which began in Britain around 1760, represents one of the most profound transformations in human history. Within roughly two centuries, societies that had been predominantly agricultural for thousands of years became predominantly industrial and urban. This transition fundamentally altered how people worked, lived, and related to one another.</p><p>The revolution was driven by a convergence of technological innovations. James Watt's improved steam engine, patented in 1769, provided a reliable power source that freed factories from dependence on water wheels. The mechanization of textile production—including the spinning jenny and power loom—dramatically increased output while reducing costs. Later, the development of railways and steamships in the 1830s and 1840s revolutionized transportation, enabling goods and people to move at unprecedented speeds. By 1850, Britain had over 10,000 kilometers of railway track, connecting industrial centers to ports and markets.</p><p>The social consequences were immense. Millions migrated from rural areas to cities, where factory work offered wages—albeit low ones. Manchester, the world's first industrial city, grew from a town of 25,000 in 1772 to over 300,000 by 1851. However, working conditions were often brutal. Children as young as five worked 12-16 hour days in dangerous conditions. The Factory Acts of the 1830s and 1840s gradually limited child labor and working hours, establishing principles of labor regulation that continue to influence policy today.</p><p>The Industrial Revolution also set in motion the sustained economic growth that has since raised living standards worldwide. However, it also initiated the large-scale burning of fossil fuels that has driven climate change. This dual legacy—unprecedented prosperity alongside environmental degradation—continues to frame debates about economic development in the 21st century. As developing nations seek to industrialize, the challenge is achieving economic growth without replicating the environmental costs that accompanied the first Industrial Revolution.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'When did the Industrial Revolution begin?',opts:['Around 1700','Around 1760','Around 1800','Around 1850'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "began in Britain around 1760."'},{type:'tf',q:'The steam engine was invented by James Watt from scratch.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段说Watt improved the steam engine，并非从头发明。'},{type:'mc',q:'What was the population of Manchester in 1851?',opts:['25,000','100,000','Over 300,000','Over 1 million'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段: "over 300,000 by 1851."'}]
},
{
    title:'26. Water Scarcity',
    text:`<h3>The Growing Global Water Crisis</h3><p>Water covers 71% of Earth's surface, yet freshwater suitable for human use is remarkably scarce. Only about 2.5% of the planet's water is freshwater, and less than 1% of that is accessible for human consumption—the rest is locked in glaciers and ice caps, or stored deep underground. As population grows and climate patterns shift, water scarcity has emerged as one of the most critical challenges of the 21st century.</p><p>The scale of the problem is staggering. According to the United Nations, 2.2 billion people lack access to safely managed drinking water, and 4.2 billion people—more than half the global population—lack safely managed sanitation. Agriculture accounts for approximately 70% of global freshwater withdrawals, and inefficient irrigation wastes significant amounts. Major rivers including the Colorado, the Yellow, and the Indus now run dry before reaching the sea during parts of the year, threatening the water supplies of hundreds of millions of people.</p><p>Climate change intensifies water stress through multiple mechanisms. Rising temperatures increase evaporation from reservoirs and soil, reducing available water. Changing precipitation patterns mean some regions experience more frequent and severe droughts, while others face destructive flooding that contaminates water supplies. The World Bank projects that water scarcity could cost some regions up to 6% of their GDP by 2050, and could displace as many as 700 million people. Competition over shared water resources has raised tensions between nations sharing river basins.</p><p>Solutions exist but require substantial investment and political will. Desalination technology—removing salt from seawater—has become more efficient, though it remains energy-intensive and expensive for many regions. Improving agricultural water efficiency through drip irrigation and drought-resistant crops offers significant potential. Wastewater recycling, already widely practiced in water-scarce countries like Singapore and Israel, provides a reliable water source. Experts emphasize that there is no single solution; rather, a combination of technological, behavioral, and policy changes is needed to avert the worst outcomes of the water crisis.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of Earth\'s water is accessible freshwater for human use?',opts:['25%','2.5%','Less than 1%','0.1%'],ans:'2',exp:'第一段: "less than 1% of that is accessible."'},{type:'tf',q:'Agriculture accounts for about 40% of global freshwater use.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: "approximately 70% of global freshwater withdrawals."'},{type:'mc',q:'How many people could be displaced by water scarcity by 2050?',opts:['100 million','300 million','500 million','700 million'],ans:'3',exp:'第三段: "as many as 700 million people."'}]
},
{
    title:'27. Immigration and Cultural Identity',
    text:`<h3>Immigration, Identity, and the Multicultural Society</h3><p>Human migration is as old as humanity itself, but the scale and pace of international movement have increased dramatically in recent decades. According to the UN, there were approximately 281 million international migrants in 2020—3.6% of the global population, up from 2.8% in 2000. This movement of people has profound implications for both migrants and host societies, particularly around questions of cultural identity.</p><p>For immigrants, navigating between cultures presents both opportunities and challenges. Many experience what sociologists call "bicultural identity"—maintaining strong ties to their heritage culture while also adopting elements of the new culture. Research suggests bicultural individuals often demonstrate greater cognitive flexibility and creativity, benefiting from exposure to multiple worldviews. However, the process of acculturation can also involve significant stress. Language barriers, discrimination, and the loss of familiar social networks contribute to what is termed "acculturative stress," which has been linked to higher rates of anxiety and depression among immigrant populations.</p><p>Host societies grapple with their own identity questions. Some view immigration as enriching—bringing new cuisines, traditions, perspectives, and entrepreneurial energy. Cities like Toronto, London, and Sydney proudly identify as multicultural. However, others fear that immigration threatens national identity and social cohesion. Political movements opposing immigration have gained support in many Western democracies over the past decade, often framing immigration as a threat to cultural continuity. Research consistently shows that the economic impact of immigration is generally positive, but public perception often differs from economic reality.</p><p>The question of integration—how immigrants and host societies adapt to each other—remains central to policy debates. Models range from "melting pot" assimilation, where immigrants are expected to adopt the dominant culture, to multiculturalism, where cultural differences are recognized and accommodated. Most experts now advocate for "interculturalism"—an approach emphasizing dialogue, interaction, and shared values rather than either forced assimilation or cultural separation. The success of diverse societies appears to depend less on the specific model chosen than on policies and attitudes that promote equal opportunity and mutual respect.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of the global population were international migrants in 2020?',opts:['2.8%','3.6%','5%','10%'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "3.6% of the global population."'},{type:'tf',q:'Research shows immigration has a generally negative economic impact.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段最后: "economic impact of immigration is generally positive."'},{type:'mc',q:'What does "interculturalism" emphasize?',opts:['Forced assimilation','Cultural separation','Dialogue and interaction','Returning to home country'],ans:'2',exp:'第四段: "emphasizing dialogue, interaction, and shared values."'}]
},
{
    title:'28. The Rise of E-commerce',
    text:`<h3>How E-commerce Transformed Global Retail</h3><p>Electronic commerce—buying and selling goods online—has fundamentally reshaped the global retail landscape. From humble beginnings in the 1990s, e-commerce has grown to account for approximately 19% of all retail sales worldwide in 2023, representing trillions of dollars in annual transactions. This transformation has affected everything from consumer behavior to urban planning, supply chains to employment patterns.</p><p>Several factors drove this growth. Improved internet access and smartphone adoption created a vast potential customer base. Secure online payment systems addressed early concerns about fraud. Companies like Amazon invested billions in logistics networks that enable same-day or next-day delivery, setting expectations that traditional retailers struggled to match. The COVID-19 pandemic accelerated the shift dramatically—global e-commerce grew by over 25% in 2020 alone as lockdowns forced consumers online. Many shopping habits formed during the pandemic have persisted even as restrictions lifted.</p><p>The consequences for traditional retail have been severe. In the United States, an estimated 15,000 retail stores closed in 2020, and the trend continued. Shopping malls, once central to suburban social life, have seen declining foot traffic and anchor store closures—a phenomenon termed the "retail apocalypse." However, the picture is nuanced. Many retailers have successfully adopted "omnichannel" strategies—combining online ordering with physical pickup, using stores as showrooms, and integrating digital tools into the in-store experience. The most successful retailers are those that have embraced both digital and physical channels.</p><p>E-commerce also raises significant concerns. The environmental cost of packaging and delivery—particularly returns—is substantial. An estimated 30% of online purchases are returned, compared to about 9% for in-store purchases, and returned items often end up in landfills. Labor practices in e-commerce warehouses have attracted criticism over working conditions and job security. Additionally, the dominance of a few large platforms raises questions about market concentration. As e-commerce continues to evolve, regulators grapple with how to balance innovation with consumer protection, worker rights, and environmental sustainability.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of global retail sales did e-commerce account for in 2023?',opts:['About 10%','About 19%','About 30%','About 50%'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "approximately 19% of all retail sales."'},{type:'tf',q:'E-commerce growth slowed during the COVID-19 pandemic.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: "accelerated the shift dramatically—grew by over 25% in 2020."'},{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of online purchases are returned?',opts:['About 9%','About 20%','About 30%','About 50%'],ans:'2',exp:'第四段: "An estimated 30% of online purchases are returned."'}]
},
{
    title:'29. Circadian Rhythms and Sleep Science',
    text:`<h3>The Science of Our Internal Clocks</h3><p>Every living organism, from single-celled bacteria to humans, operates according to internal biological clocks known as circadian rhythms. These roughly 24-hour cycles regulate sleep, hormone production, body temperature, metabolism, and numerous other physiological processes. The 2017 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded to three scientists who elucidated the molecular mechanisms controlling these rhythms, underscoring their fundamental importance to health.</p><p>The master clock in humans resides in the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN), a tiny region of the brain containing about 20,000 neurons. The SCN receives light signals from the eyes and synchronizes peripheral clocks found in virtually every organ and tissue. When this system functions properly, different bodily processes occur at optimal times—alertness peaks during daylight hours, while cellular repair and memory consolidation occur primarily during sleep. Disruption of these rhythms, such as through shift work or jet lag, has been linked to increased risks of obesity, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and certain cancers.</p><p>Modern lifestyles pose unprecedented challenges to circadian health. The widespread use of artificial lighting and electronic screens exposes people to blue light at night, which suppresses melatonin—the hormone that signals the body to prepare for sleep. Research shows that using smartphones before bed delays sleep onset by an average of 30 minutes and reduces REM sleep duration. Teenagers are particularly vulnerable, as biological changes during adolescence naturally shift sleep timing later, while early school start times force them to wake before their bodies are ready. Some school districts that have delayed start times to 8:30am or later have observed improvements in attendance, grades, and student well-being.</p><p>Sleep scientists recommend several practices for maintaining healthy circadian rhythms: maintaining consistent sleep and wake times—even on weekends, maximizing exposure to natural light during the day, dimming lights and avoiding screens for at least an hour before bed, and keeping the bedroom cool and dark. While these recommendations may seem simple, implementing them in a world designed around 24/7 connectivity remains a significant challenge. Growing awareness of sleep's importance, however, is driving cultural shifts—from corporate wellness programs to the rise of "sleep tourism" at hotels offering specialized sleep amenities.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'Where is the master circadian clock located in humans?',opts:['The heart','The liver','The suprachiasmatic nucleus','The pineal gland'],ans:'2',exp:'第二段: "in the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN)."'},{type:'tf',q:'Using smartphones before bed can delay sleep onset by 30 minutes on average.',ans:'true',exp:'第三段明确提到delays sleep onset by an average of 30 minutes。'},{type:'mc',q:'What hormone does blue light suppress?',opts:['Cortisol','Adrenaline','Serotonin','Melatonin'],ans:'3',exp:'第三段: "suppresses melatonin—the hormone that signals the body to prepare for sleep."'}]
},
{
    title:'30. Youth Unemployment',
    text:`<h3>Addressing the Global Youth Employment Crisis</h3><p>Youth unemployment is among the most persistent and troubling features of the global labor market. The International Labour Organization (ILO) reports that young people aged 15-24 are three times more likely to be unemployed than adults over 25. In 2022, the global youth unemployment rate stood at approximately 15.6%, affecting over 70 million young people actively seeking work. Beyond the immediate economic cost, long-term youth unemployment carries lasting consequences for individuals, communities, and entire economies.</p><p>The causes are multifaceted. One major factor is the mismatch between education systems and labor market needs. Many graduates enter the workforce with theoretical knowledge but lack the practical skills employers seek. A 2021 McKinsey survey found that 43% of employers reported difficulty filling entry-level positions due to skills gaps. Economic downturns disproportionately affect young workers, as companies freeze hiring and lay off less experienced staff. In some countries, rigid labor regulations that protect existing workers inadvertently make employers reluctant to hire new permanent staff.</p><p>The consequences of prolonged youth unemployment extend far beyond lost income. Research documents "scarring effects"—young people who experience extended unemployment early in their careers earn less and face higher unemployment risk throughout their working lives. The psychological toll includes increased rates of depression, anxiety, and social withdrawal. At a societal level, high youth unemployment is correlated with social unrest, crime, and political instability. The economic cost in lost productivity and reduced lifetime earnings runs into trillions of dollars globally.</p><p>Effective solutions combine multiple approaches. Germany's dual education system, which combines classroom learning with paid on-the-job training, has kept youth unemployment consistently below 8%—among the lowest in Europe. Apprenticeship programs and vocational training can bridge the education-employment gap. Entrepreneurship support—access to credit, mentorship, and simplified business registration—can help young people create their own opportunities. Digital skills training is particularly important, as the technology sector continues to generate new job categories. The ILO emphasizes that addressing youth unemployment requires coordinated action from governments, educational institutions, and the private sector.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'How many times more likely are young people to be unemployed compared to adults?',opts:['Twice as likely','Three times as likely','Four times as likely','Five times as likely'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "three times more likely to be unemployed."'},{type:'tf',q:'Germany\'s youth unemployment rate is among the highest in Europe.',ans:'false',exp:'第四段: "among the lowest in Europe."'},{type:'mc',q:'What do "scarring effects" refer to?',opts:['Physical injuries at work','Lasting negative impact of early-career unemployment','Visible marks on CVs','Skin conditions from stress'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "earn less and face higher unemployment risk throughout their working lives."'}]
},
{
    title:'31. Genetic Engineering in Agriculture',
    text:`<h3>GM Crops: Promise, Controversy, and the Future of Food</h3><p>Genetic engineering in agriculture—the direct manipulation of an organism's DNA to introduce desirable traits—has been one of the most controversial scientific advances of recent decades. Since the first genetically modified (GM) crop was approved for commercial sale in 1994, GM varieties have been adopted across vast agricultural areas. As of 2023, approximately 190 million hectares of GM crops are grown globally, primarily soybeans, maize, cotton, and canola, across 29 countries.</p><p>Proponents argue that genetic engineering offers solutions to pressing agricultural challenges. Herbicide-resistant crops allow farmers to control weeds more effectively with less tillage, reducing soil erosion. Insect-resistant Bt crops, engineered to produce a protein toxic to specific pests, have reduced insecticide use by an estimated 37% while increasing yields by 22% on average, according to a 2014 meta-analysis. More recent applications aim at nutritional enhancement—"Golden Rice," engineered to produce beta-carotene to combat vitamin A deficiency that causes blindness in millions of children in developing countries. Climate-resilient traits like drought tolerance could become increasingly important as global temperatures rise.</p><p>Critics raise concerns on several fronts. Environmental risks include potential gene flow from GM crops to wild relatives, creating herbicide-resistant "superweeds," and unintended effects on non-target organisms like beneficial insects. The dominance of a few large corporations in the GM seed market raises concerns about farmer dependence and reduced agricultural biodiversity. Many consumers, particularly in Europe, express strong preferences for non-GM food, driven by health concerns despite scientific consensus that approved GM foods pose no greater risk than conventional foods. Mandatory labeling laws in over 60 countries reflect these consumer concerns.</p><p>Newer techniques like CRISPR gene editing are blurring regulatory categories. Unlike traditional GM, which inserts foreign DNA, gene editing can make precise changes within an organism's existing genome, mimicking mutations that could occur naturally. Some countries, including the US and Japan, have adopted more permissive regulations for gene-edited crops, while the EU has historically applied similar restrictions to both GM and gene-edited organisms. As climate change intensifies pressure on food systems, the debate between precaution and innovation in agricultural biotechnology grows increasingly urgent.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'Bt crops have increased insecticide use on average.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: "reduced insecticide use by an estimated 37%."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is Golden Rice engineered to produce?',opts:['Vitamin C','Vitamin D','Beta-carotene','Iron'],ans:'2',exp:'第二段: "engineered to produce beta-carotene."'},{type:'mc',q:'How many countries have mandatory GM labeling laws?',opts:['About 20','About 40','Over 60','Over 100'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段最后: "Mandatory labeling laws in over 60 countries."'}]
},
{
    title:'32. The Anthropology of Food',
    text:`<h3>What Food Reveals About Human Culture</h3><p>Food is far more than mere sustenance. Across all human societies, what people eat, how they prepare it, and with whom they share it reflects deep cultural values, social structures, and historical influences. The anthropology of food examines eating not as a biological necessity but as a profoundly social and symbolic act—one that helps define identity, reinforce relationships, and express beliefs.</p><p>Every culture has food rules and taboos that mark group boundaries. These may be religious, as with Islamic halal and Jewish kosher dietary laws, or cultural, such as the strong aversion to eating dog meat in Western societies while it remains acceptable in parts of East Asia. What is considered a delicacy in one culture—raw fish in Japan, fermented shark in Iceland, insects in parts of Africa and Latin America—may provoke disgust in another. These differences are not random but reflect histories of ecological adaptation, religious influence, and cultural exchange. The French sociologist Pierre Bourdieu argued that food preferences also signal social class, with "taste" serving as a marker of cultural capital and group membership.</p><p>Food rituals play central roles in social bonding. The family dinner, the business lunch, the wedding feast, and the religious fasting period all use food to structure social relationships and mark significant occasions. Commensality—the act of eating together—has been shown to build trust and cooperation. Research among firefighters found that teams who cooked and ate together performed better in coordinated tasks than those who ate separately. Conversely, refusing to share food with someone can be a powerful social exclusion signal.</p><p>Globalization is transforming food cultures in complex ways. On one hand, the spread of multinational food chains and processed foods has been criticized for homogenizing diets and contributing to public health problems. On the other hand, globalization has also increased access to diverse cuisines. Sushi, once exotic outside Japan, is now globally available, while interest in traditional and local food has sparked movements like "slow food" and farm-to-table dining. The anthropology of food suggests that rather than simply converging or diverging, food cultures are constantly being reinvented through a dynamic interplay of local traditions and global influences.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'According to the passage, what are food taboos a reflection of?',opts:['Nutritional science','Religious influence, ecological adaptation, and cultural exchange','Government regulations','Food safety standards'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "reflect histories of ecological adaptation, religious influence, and cultural exchange."'},{type:'tf',q:'Commensality refers to the practice of cooking alone.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段: "the act of eating together."'},{type:'mc',q:'What did research on firefighters find?',opts:['They preferred eating alone','Teams that ate together performed better','Food had no impact on teamwork','Firefighters disliked shared meals'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "teams who cooked and ate together performed better."'}]
},
{
    title:'33. Depression and Modern Society',
    text:`<h3>Understanding Depression in the Modern World</h3><p>Depression is now the leading cause of disability worldwide, affecting approximately 280 million people—about 3.8% of the global population—according to the World Health Organization. While depression has existed throughout human history, rates have risen significantly in recent decades, particularly among young people. This increase has prompted researchers to examine how features of modern society might contribute to this growing mental health crisis.</p><p>The causes of depression are complex, involving an interplay of genetic, biological, psychological, and social factors. Some individuals inherit a greater vulnerability, but environmental triggers typically activate this predisposition. Modern risk factors identified by researchers include social isolation—despite unprecedented digital connectivity, people report fewer close confidants than in previous generations. The erosion of community structures, declining religious participation, and the rise of single-person households have reduced traditional sources of social support. Economic insecurity, including precarious employment and stagnant wages, contributes to chronic stress. Social media use has been linked to increased depression risk among adolescents, possibly through social comparison and sleep disruption.</p><p>There is also growing recognition of how modern environments affect mental health. Sedentary lifestyles, reduced time in nature, disrupted sleep from artificial lighting, and ultra-processed diets have all been associated with higher depression risk. The concept of "evolutionary mismatch" suggests that human brains evolved for conditions vastly different from modern life—small social groups, physical activity, natural light cycles—and that the mismatch between our ancestral environment and current living conditions contributes to mental health vulnerability.</p><p>Treatment approaches have expanded beyond medication. While antidepressant drugs remain commonly prescribed—with global use increasing by over 60% between 2000 and 2015—cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) has strong evidence for effectiveness. Lifestyle interventions including exercise, improved sleep, dietary changes, and social prescribing (connecting patients with community activities) are gaining recognition. Many experts now advocate a "biopsychosocial" approach that addresses biological, psychological, and social dimensions simultaneously. Reducing stigma has been a major success of public health campaigns, though barriers to accessing mental healthcare persist in most countries.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'How many people globally are affected by depression?',opts:['About 100 million','About 150 million','About 280 million','About 500 million'],ans:'2',exp:'第一段: "approximately 280 million people."'},{type:'tf',q:'Antidepressant use decreased between 2000 and 2015.',ans:'false',exp:'第四段: "global use increasing by over 60% between 2000 and 2015."'},{type:'mc',q:'What does "evolutionary mismatch" suggest?',opts:['Evolution has stopped','Human brains are adapted to conditions different from modern life','Depression does not exist in nature','Evolution only affects physical traits'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "human brains evolved for conditions vastly different from modern life."'}]
},
{
    title:'34. Urban Planning and Smart Cities',
    text:`<h3>Designing the Cities of Tomorrow</h3><p>By 2050, approximately 68% of the global population is projected to live in urban areas, up from 56% in 2020. This unprecedented urbanization—adding roughly 2.5 billion people to cities—presents both immense challenges and opportunities. How cities are planned and designed will profoundly influence quality of life, economic productivity, and environmental sustainability for much of humanity.</p><p>Traditional urban planning has often prioritized automobile movement over human experience. Wide roads, sprawling suburbs, and separated land uses created cities where daily activities require driving. This model has been criticized for promoting sedentary lifestyles, consuming excessive land, generating pollution, and isolating people who cannot drive. In response, concepts like "15-minute cities"—where residents can access work, shopping, education, healthcare, and recreation within a 15-minute walk or bike ride—have gained international attention. Paris has been a pioneer, with Mayor Anne Hidalgo implementing extensive bike lanes, pedestrianized streets, and neighborhood-level services.</p><p>Technology offers new tools for urban management. Sensors monitoring air quality, traffic flow, energy consumption, and waste management generate data that can optimize city operations. Singapore's "Smart Nation" initiative uses real-time traffic data to reduce congestion, while Barcelona's smart water system has reduced water consumption by 25%. However, "smart city" technologies raise concerns about privacy, surveillance, and algorithmic bias. Critics warn that cities optimized for efficiency may become less livable if citizen participation and social equity are not prioritized alongside technological innovation.</p><p>The most forward-thinking urban designs integrate green infrastructure as essential systems rather than aesthetic additions. Green roofs and walls reduce building energy use and stormwater runoff. Urban forests combat the heat island effect—cities can be up to 7°C warmer than surrounding areas—while absorbing carbon and providing wildlife habitat. Cities like Copenhagen and Amsterdam demonstrate how prioritizing cycling, public transit, and pedestrian spaces creates more livable environments. The challenge for rapidly growing cities in the developing world, which face the greatest infrastructure deficits, is accessing the resources and expertise needed to implement sustainable urban planning.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'More than 80% of the global population will live in cities by 2050.',ans:'false',exp:'第一段: "approximately 68% of the global population."'},{type:'mc',q:'What are "15-minute cities"?',opts:['Cities with 15-minute traffic lights','Cities where daily needs are accessible within a 15-minute walk','Cities planned in 15-minute meetings','Cities that took 15 minutes to build'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段明确说明15-minute cities的含义。'},{type:'mc',q:'How much did Barcelona\'s smart water system reduce water consumption?',opts:['10%','15%','25%','50%'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段: "reduced water consumption by 25%."'}]
},
{
    title:'35. The History of the English Language',
    text:`<h3>The Evolution of Global English</h3><p>English is spoken by approximately 1.5 billion people worldwide—about 400 million as a first language and over 1 billion as a second or foreign language. Its journey from a dialect spoken by a few Germanic tribes on an island off the European coast to the world's dominant lingua franca is one of the most remarkable linguistic stories in history.</p><p>The English language has been shaped by waves of invasion and cultural contact. Old English (450-1100 CE) emerged from the Germanic languages of Angles, Saxons, and Jutes who settled Britain after Roman withdrawal. Viking invasions brought Old Norse influences, contributing everyday words like "sky," "window," and "they." The Norman Conquest of 1066 transformed the language most dramatically, introducing thousands of French and Latin words. This created the characteristic split in English vocabulary where formal/technical terms often have Latinate origins ("commence," "terminate") while everyday equivalents are Germanic ("start," "end").</p><p>The modern period saw English spread through British colonialism to North America, Australia, Africa, and South Asia, where it evolved into distinct varieties. American English preserves features lost in British English—the pronunciation of "r" in words like "car" and the past participle "gotten." The 20th century cemented English as a global language through American economic, cultural, and technological dominance. Hollywood films, popular music, and later the internet—where approximately 60% of content is in English—spread American English globally.</p><p>Today, the status of English raises complex questions. It provides enormous advantages to native speakers in global commerce, academia, and diplomacy. Non-native speakers vastly outnumber native speakers, and "World Englishes"—Indian English, Singaporean English, Nigerian English—have developed their own distinctive features. Some linguists argue these varieties should be recognized as legitimate forms rather than treated as "incorrect" English. Meanwhile, the dominance of English contributes to the decline of minority languages, with an estimated one language dying every two weeks.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'How many people speak English as a first language?',opts:['About 200 million','About 400 million','About 800 million','About 1.5 billion'],ans:'1',exp:'第一段: "about 400 million as a first language."'},{type:'tf',q:'The Norman Conquest of 1066 introduced Germanic vocabulary to English.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: Norman Conquest introduced French and Latin words, not Germanic。'},{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of internet content is in English?',opts:['About 30%','About 60%','About 80%','About 95%'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "approximately 60% of content is in English."'}]
},
{
    title:'36. Nuclear Energy Debate',
    text:`<h3>Nuclear Power: Essential Climate Solution or Unacceptable Risk?</h3><p>Few energy sources provoke as much controversy as nuclear power. Supporters present it as essential for addressing climate change—a reliable source of low-carbon electricity that can complement intermittent renewables. Opponents cite catastrophic accidents, unresolved waste storage challenges, and high costs. The debate has gained urgency as countries seek to decarbonize their energy systems while maintaining reliable electricity supplies.</p><p>The climate case for nuclear energy is straightforward. Nuclear plants produce electricity with virtually no direct CO2 emissions. Lifecycle analyses accounting for construction, mining, and decommissioning show nuclear emissions comparable to wind and substantially lower than solar—and far below fossil fuels. France, which generates about 70% of its electricity from nuclear power, has per capita electricity-sector emissions roughly 80% lower than Germany, which phased out nuclear while maintaining coal generation. Many climate scientists and environmentalists, including some former opponents, now argue that achieving net-zero emissions by 2050 without nuclear energy is extremely difficult.</p><p>However, serious concerns persist. The 1986 Chernobyl disaster and 2011 Fukushima accident demonstrated that nuclear accidents, while rare, have catastrophic consequences. The long-term storage of radioactive waste remains unresolved—high-level waste remains hazardous for tens of thousands of years. Finland's Onkalo repository, the world's first permanent geological storage facility, took decades to develop and faces ongoing safety debates. Nuclear weapons proliferation is another concern; the technology and materials for civilian nuclear programs can potentially be diverted to weapons development. Additionally, nuclear plants are extremely expensive, with construction typically taking 10-15 years and facing cost overruns.</p><p>The future of nuclear energy likely depends on new technologies. Small modular reactors (SMRs), which can be factory-built and deployed more quickly than traditional plants, have attracted significant investment. Fusion energy—the process that powers the sun—has seen breakthroughs including net energy gain achieved at the US National Ignition Facility in 2022. However, commercial fusion remains decades away. The nuclear debate reflects a deeper tension in environmental thinking: whether to prioritize the precautionary principle or accept calculated risks in pursuit of decarbonization.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of France\'s electricity comes from nuclear power?',opts:['About 30%','About 50%','About 70%','About 90%'],ans:'2',exp:'第二段: "about 70% of its electricity from nuclear power."'},{type:'tf',q:'Nuclear power produces large amounts of direct CO2 emissions.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: "with virtually no direct CO2 emissions."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is the name of Finland\'s permanent nuclear waste repository?',opts:['Fukushima','Chernobyl','Onkalo','SMR'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段: "Finland\'s Onkalo repository."'}]
},
{
    title:'37. Gender Equality in the Workplace',
    text:`<h3>The Persistent Challenge of Workplace Gender Equality</h3><p>Despite decades of progress in women's labor force participation and educational attainment, significant gender gaps persist in workplaces worldwide. Women globally earn approximately 20% less than men on average, hold only about 28% of managerial positions, and occupy barely 8% of CEO positions at Fortune 500 companies. Understanding why these gaps persist—and what can be done—has become a central concern for policymakers, businesses, and researchers.</p><p>Research has identified multiple contributing factors. The "motherhood penalty" is well-documented: women's earnings tend to decline after having children, while men often receive a "fatherhood bonus." This disparity results partly from women being more likely to take career breaks or reduce working hours for childcare. Occupational segregation also plays a role—women are overrepresented in lower-paying sectors such as education, healthcare, and social services, while men dominate higher-paying fields like technology, finance, and engineering. Even within the same occupation, women are less likely to negotiate starting salaries and less likely to be promoted to senior roles.</p><p>Unconscious bias compounds structural factors. Studies using identical CVs with male and female names find that both male and female evaluators rate male candidates as more competent and offer them higher starting salaries. Women face a "double bind" in leadership: assertiveness is often perceived negatively in women while valued in men. This creates a challenging dynamic where the behaviors expected of leaders conflict with gender stereotypes about how women "should" behave. The #MeToo movement drew global attention to workplace harassment, another barrier that disproportionately affects women.</p><p>Policy responses vary widely. Iceland has implemented mandatory equal pay certification for companies with over 25 employees. Several European countries require gender quotas for corporate boards, with Norway pioneering this approach in 2003. Transparency measures—requiring companies to report gender pay gaps—have been adopted in the UK, Australia, and elsewhere. Research on the effectiveness of unconscious bias training is mixed, with some studies finding short-term effects but limited lasting behavioral change. Most experts agree that multiple approaches—combining policy mandates, organizational culture change, and individual-level interventions—are necessary to meaningfully close workplace gender gaps.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of Fortune 500 CEO positions are held by women?',opts:['About 8%','About 20%','About 28%','About 50%'],ans:'0',exp:'第一段: "barely 8% of CEO positions at Fortune 500 companies."'},{type:'tf',q:'The "fatherhood bonus" refers to men earning less after having children.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: men receive a "fatherhood bonus"—higher earnings after having children。'},{type:'mc',q:'Which country pioneered mandatory corporate board gender quotas?',opts:['Iceland','Norway','UK','Australia'],ans:'1',exp:'第四段: "Norway pioneering this approach in 2003."'}]
},
{
    title:'38. Tourism\'s Impact on Local Communities',
    text:`<h3>Mass Tourism: Economic Lifeline or Cultural Threat?</h3><p>International tourism grew from 25 million arrivals in 1950 to over 1.5 billion in 2019, making it one of the world's largest industries. For many destinations, tourism provides vital income and employment. Yet the rapid growth of mass tourism has sparked intense debate about its effects on local communities, cultural heritage, and the environment.</p><p>The economic benefits of tourism are substantial. The industry accounts for approximately 10% of global GDP and employs about 1 in 10 workers worldwide. For developing countries, tourism can be a crucial source of foreign currency and a catalyst for infrastructure development. Countries like Thailand, where tourism represents about 20% of GDP, and the Maldives, where the figure exceeds countries dependent on the sector face severe hardship when tourism is disrupted—as demonstrated during the COVID-19 pandemic. Tourism also creates markets for local crafts, cuisine, and cultural performances, potentially helping preserve traditions.</p><p>However, overtourism has reached crisis levels in many destinations. Venice, with only 50,000 permanent residents, receives up to 30 million visitors annually, straining infrastructure and driving housing costs beyond local affordability. Barcelona residents have organized protests against tourism's impact on housing and neighborhood character. In Thailand's Maya Bay, made famous by a film, visitor numbers reached 5,000 daily, devastating the coral ecosystem until authorities closed it for rehabilitation in 2018. Even the environmental cost of long-haul flights undermines another aspect of sustainability.</p><p>Sustainable tourism initiatives offer alternatives. Bhutan's "high value, low impact" model charges tourists a daily fee ($200-250) that funds education and healthcare while limiting visitor numbers. Community-based tourism, where local residents manage and benefit from tourism enterprises directly, has shown success in countries from Costa Rica to Namibia. The pandemic disruption created opportunities to rethink tourism models, with destinations from Amsterdam to New Zealand exploring ways to attract fewer, higher-spending visitors who stay longer. The challenge is balancing tourism's genuine economic benefits with the preservation of the very things—beautiful environments, vibrant cultures, livable communities—that attract visitors in the first place.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'What percentage of global GDP does tourism account for?',opts:['About 5%','About 10%','About 15%','About 20%'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "approximately 10% of global GDP."'},{type:'tf',q:'Venice has a permanent population of about 500,000 residents.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段: "only 50,000 permanent residents."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is Bhutan\'s tourism model called?',opts:['Mass tourism','High value, low impact','Budget tourism','Unlimited tourism'],ans:'1',exp:'第四段: "high value, low impact model."'}]
},
{
    title:'39. The Neuroscience of Learning',
    text:`<h3>How Understanding the Brain Can Improve Education</h3><p>Recent advances in neuroscience have provided unprecedented insights into how the brain learns. Techniques such as functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) allow researchers to observe brain activity during learning tasks, revealing neural mechanisms that underpin memory, attention, and skill acquisition. While translating laboratory findings into classroom practice remains challenging, the emerging field of "educational neuroscience" offers promising directions for improving teaching and learning.</p><p>One well-established finding is the importance of active recall—retrieving information from memory—for durable learning. Students typically prefer re-reading and highlighting, but research consistently shows that testing oneself on material produces stronger long-term retention. This "testing effect" works because retrieving a memory strengthens neural pathways and makes future retrieval easier. Spaced repetition—reviewing material at gradually increasing intervals—exploits the brain's forgetting curve to optimize retention. Both principles are increasingly incorporated into educational software and study techniques, though they remain underused in many classrooms.</p><p>Neuroscience also illuminates the role of emotion in learning. The amygdala, a brain region central to emotional processing, interacts with the hippocampus—crucial for memory formation—meaning emotionally engaging content is more likely to be remembered. This has implications for curriculum design: connecting abstract concepts to personally meaningful contexts can enhance learning. However, excessive stress impairs learning; chronic stress elevates cortisol, which can damage hippocampal neurons and inhibit memory formation. This research supports the common-sense observation that anxious, unsafe, or highly pressured learning environments are counterproductive.</p><p>Perhaps most practically relevant is the finding that intelligence is far more malleable than once believed. The concept of neuroplasticity—the brain's capacity to reorganize itself by forming new neural connections throughout life—undermines fixed notions of intelligence and talent. Studies show that teaching students about neuroplasticity—that intelligence can grow through effort—improves academic performance, particularly for struggling students. This "growth mindset" intervention, when properly implemented, helps students persist through challenges rather than interpreting difficulty as evidence of permanent inability. While neuroscience is not a magic solution for education's complex challenges, it provides a scientific foundation for approaches that many effective teachers have long practiced intuitively.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'tf',q:'Re-reading is the most effective study technique for long-term retention.',ans:'false',exp:'第二段: research shows testing produces stronger retention than re-reading。'},{type:'mc',q:'What brain region is crucial for memory formation?',opts:['Amygdala','Hippocampus','Cerebellum','Brain stem'],ans:'1',exp:'第三段: "the hippocampus—crucial for memory formation."'},{type:'mc',q:'What is neuroplasticity?',opts:['The brain\'s fixed structure','The brain\'s capacity to form new neural connections','A type of brain surgery','A learning disability'],ans:'1',exp:'第四段: "the brain\'s capacity to reorganize itself by forming new neural connections."'}]
},
{
    title:'40. Globalization and Local Cultures',
    text:`<h3>Does Globalization Mean Cultural Homogenization?</h3><p>Globalization—the increasing interconnectedness of economies, societies, and cultures—has been accused of creating a homogenized global monoculture dominated by Western, particularly American, influences. From McDonald's in Moscow to Hollywood films in Mumbai, critics see the erosion of distinct local cultures. However, the reality of cultural globalization is more complex and multidirectional than the homogenization thesis suggests.</p><p>There is undeniably substance to concerns about cultural standardization. English has become the de facto global language of business, science, and the internet. Global brands—Starbucks, Nike, Apple—create similar consumer landscapes from Shanghai to São Paulo. The concentration of media production in a few countries means a limited range of cultural perspectives reaches global audiences. UNESCO estimates that 50% of global film and television content originates from the United States. The extinction of languages—approximately half of the world's 7,000 languages are endangered—represents an irreversible loss of cultural diversity.</p><p>However, cultural flows are not one-way. The global popularity of Japanese anime, Korean K-pop and K-dramas (the "Korean Wave"), Bollywood films, and Latin American telenovelas demonstrates cultural influence from multiple directions. Furthermore, global cultural products are typically adapted—or "localized"—rather than simply adopted unchanged. McDonald's serves vegetarian burgers in India, rice dishes in East Asia, and halal meat in Muslim-majority countries. The process of cultural mixing, termed "hybridization" or "creolization" by anthropologists, creates new cultural forms rather than simply replacing local ones with global imports.</p><p>Technology has also empowered local cultural expression. Digital platforms allow artists, musicians, and filmmakers to reach global audiences without traditional gatekeepers. Indigenous communities use digital tools to document and revitalize endangered languages. Social media enables diaspora communities to maintain cultural connections across vast distances. Rather than a simple story of Western cultural domination, contemporary globalization involves complex cultural negotiation—some traditions are lost, others are transformed, and entirely new cultural expressions emerge from the intersection of local and global influences.</p>`,
    qs:[{type:'mc',q:'According to UNESCO, what percentage of global film and TV content originates from the US?',opts:['25%','50%','75%','90%'],ans:'1',exp:'第二段: "50% of global film and television content."'},{type:'tf',q:'Cultural globalization only flows from the West to the rest of the world.',ans:'false',exp:'第三段: Korean Wave, Bollywood, anime demonstrate cultural influence from multiple directions。'},{type:'mc',q:'What term do anthropologists use for cultural mixing?',opts:['Homogenization','Standardization','Hybridization or creolization','Americanization'],ans:'2',exp:'第三段: "termed hybridization or creolization by anthropologists."'}]
}
);
